[00:53:32] [33mWARN[39m: [36mPOST /api/companies/3422f81a-8ca2-4ce1-aae5-5cf8ce34fa0e/issues 422[39m [90m{"reqBody":{"title":"[Strategy Analyst] Deploy Short-Side Breakout Strategy for Strong Trending-Down GC Regime","description":"CONTEXT: Mean-reversion is explicitly contraindicated here. ADX=50 with trending_down regime means price is in persistent one-directional flow — do NOT deploy any further mean-reversion variants. The positive outlier (gs_v3, Sharpe=1.02) succeeded because it accidentally traded WITH the session's directional open, not against it.\n\nSTRATEGY LOGIC: Implement a short-side breakout strategy that enters SHORT when price breaks BELOW the 20-bar rolling low (on 5-min bars during RTH), confirmed by close of a 2nd bar below the breakout level to avoid fakeouts. Trend filter: only take trades when 50-EMA slope is negative (price < EMA50). ADX gate: only trade when ADX > 30 to ensure we stay in trend regime.\n\nEXACT PARAMETERS TO TEST:\n- lookback_period: 20 bars (captures intraday structure without being too slow)\n- atr_period: 14 bars for volatility normalization\n- atr_multiplier for breakout confirmation: 1.8x (filters noise, avoids microbreakouts)\n- stop_loss: 1.2x ATR above entry (tight, trend should not pull back significantly if valid)\n- profit_target: 3.0x ATR below entry (risk/reward = 2.5:1 minimum, essential to offset lower trade frequency)\n- confirmation_bars: 2 (must close below breakout level on bar N+1 and N+2 before entry on bar N+3 open)\n- session_filter: RTH only (09:30-16:00 ET), avoid overnight gaps contaminating signals\n- max_trades_per_session: 3 (prevent overtrading on whipsaws)\n- risk_per_trade: 1% fixed fractional\n\nRATIONALE: In a trending_down regime with ADX=50, breakout-short captures the fat tail of continued downside. The 3.0x ATR target vs 1.2x ATR stop gives a ~2.5R setup; even at 45% win rate this is profitable (expectancy > 0). This directly exploits the regime rather than fighting it.\n\nDEPLOYMENT GATES REMINDER: Backtest must clear Sharpe>=1.5, WR>=50%, PF>=1.3, DD<5%, trades>=50. With tight stops and trend confirmation, expect 60-100 trades in backtest window — if trade count is low, consider relaxing breakout_confirmation_bars to 1.\n\nIF THIS FAILS: If short_breakout also fails (Sharpe < 0), the issue is likely data quality, commission/slippage model, or the backtest window does not match the live regime period. Audit P&L attribution before generating gs_v13.\n\nRecommended parameters: {\"type\": \"short_breakout\", \"lookback_period\": 20, \"atr_multiplier\": 1.8, \"atr_period\": 14, \"breakout_confirmation_bars\": 2, \"stop_atr_multiplier\": 1.2, \"profit_target_atr_multiplier\": 3.0, \"session_filter\": \"rth_only\", \"adx_min_threshold\": 30, \"trend_filter_ema_period\": 50, \"max_trades_per_session\": 3, \"position_sizing\": \"fixed_fractional\", \"risk_per_trade_pct\": 0.01}\nRecommended class: short_breakout\nDiagnosis: Mean-reversion strategies are fundamentally misaligned with the current regime: ADX=50 signals an exceptionally strong trend, and mean-reversion logic (buying/fading dips back to VWAP) is structurally short-alpha in a persistent downtrend — high win rates (58-63%) are being overwhelmed by large adverse excursions on losing trades, producing profit factors well below 1.0 and negative Sharpe across all 8 attempts. The one strategy that posted positive Sharpe (gs_v3_orb_atr, Sharpe=1.02) was classified as session_open_breakout despite having mean-reversion params, suggesting it was accidentally capturing early-session directional momentum rather than true mean-reversion. Continuing to tune VWAP periods and entry thresholds within the mean-reversion class is a dead end in this regime.","status":"backlog","priority":"high","assigneeAgentId":"8b85ccad-060e-4dd8-b007-4eced8098223","requestDepth":0},"routePath":"/companies/:companyId/issues"}[39m
